The main advantage of OOPS is code re-usability

OOPS principles
---------------
1) Encapsulation
2) Abstraction
3) Polymorphism
4) Inheritance

========================================
Encapsulation:- 
========================================

-> Encapsulation is used to combine our variables and methods as single entity /unit

-> Encapsulation provides data hiding
-> We can achieve encapsulation using Classes

  class Demo{
  
       //variables
        
	   //methods
  }
  
  
==================================
Abstraction
----------------------------------
->  Abstraction means hiding un-necessary data and providing only required data.
	
->  We can achieve Abstraction using interfaces & abstraction classes

Ex: We will not bother about how laptop working internally.
    we will not bother about how car engine is starting internally
	
	we just have to check weather a car or laptop is working or not. so all the internal processes is hidden how its working internally
	just we are getting the output from the device or only that much of data that is required for us.
	

======================================
Polymorphism
======================================

-> Exhibiting multiple behaviours based on situation is called as Polymorphism.

Ex:-

      10 + 20 = 30   (+ is adding)  

      "hi" + "hello" = hihello   (here + is concatination)

       here + plays a polymorphic behaviour.	

       same object is playing different roles according to the situations


==============================================
Inheritance
==============================================

-> Extending the properties from one class to another calss is called as Inheritance.

-> The main aim of inheritance is code re-usability.

Ex:- child will inherit properties from parent



Note:- In java, one child can't inherit properties from two parents at a time.


==================
Class
==================
-> Class is a plan or model or template
-> Class is a blue print of object.
-> Class is used to declare variables and methods.
-> Project means collection of classes.
-> Once class is created then we can create any no. of object for class.
-> 'class' keyword is used to create classes in java 

   class <ClassName>{
      
	  //variables
	  //methods
   
   }

-> classes does not exist physically.


==============
Object
==============
-> Any real-world entitiy is called as Object.
-> Objects exist physically
-> Objects will be created based on the class.
-> Without having the class we cannot create object(class is mendatory to create objects)
-> Object creation means allocating memory in JVM 
-> 'new' keyword is used to create the object

    ClassName refVariable = new ClassName ();
	
	User u1 = new User ();
	
	User u2 = new User ();

-> Objects will be created by JVM in the runtime.	
-> Objects will be created in heap area.
-> If object is not in use then Garbage collector will remove that object from heap.
-> Garbage Collector is responsible for memory cleanup activities in JVM heap area.	
-> GC will remove only unused object from heap area. which is managed by JVM, we cannot manage and control GC.
